Exception handling 


Exception Handling in Simple Terms
Imagine you are withdrawing money from an ATM. If you enter an amount greater than your account balance, the ATM shows an error message instead of crashing. This is similar to exception handling in Javaâ€”it helps prevent a program from crashing when something unexpected happens.

What is an Exception?
An exception is an error that occurs during program execution. If not handled, it stops the program.

Example of an exception:

java
Copy
Edit
int a = 10;
int b = 0;
int c = a / b; // This will cause an error (ArithmeticException)
Since division by zero is not allowed, the program will crash.

How to Handle Exceptions?
We use try, catch, and finally blocks.

try â€“ The risky code goes inside this block.
catch â€“ Catches and handles the exception.
finally â€“ Runs whether an exception occurs or not (optional).
Example: Handling Division by Zero
java
Copy
Edit
public class ExceptionExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int a = 10;
            int b = 0;
            int c = a / b; // Risky code
            System.out.println(c);
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Error: Division by zero is not allowed.");
        }
        System.out.println("Program continues...");
    }
}
Output:

vbnet
Copy
Edit
Error: Division by zero is not allowed.
Program continues...
Without exception handling, the program would crash. With exception handling, it displays an error message and continues execution.

Types of Exceptions
Checked Exceptions â€“ Must be handled (e.g., IOException, SQLException).
Unchecked Exceptions â€“ Occur at runtime (e.g., ArithmeticException, NullPointerException).
Using finally
java
Copy
Edit
try {
    int num = 5 / 0;
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Caught exception: " + e);
} finally {
    System.out.println("This block always executes.");
}
Throwing Custom Exceptions
You can create your own exception using throw.

java
Copy
Edit
class CustomExceptionExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int age = 15;
        if (age < 18) {
            throw new ArithmeticException("You must be 18 or older.");
        }
        System.out.println("You are eligible.");
    }
}
Output:

